# C++ Standards

## Language & Style
- C++17 strictly; no raw owning pointers — use `std::unique_ptr`, `QScopedPointer`, or Qt parent ownership
- `#pragma once` in all headers, no include guards
- One class per `.h`/`.cpp` pair, filename matches class name
- `PascalCase` for classes, `camelCase` for methods and variables, `m_` prefix for private members
- `SCREAMING_SNAKE_CASE` for constants and enum values

## Qt Specifics
- Signals/slots via `connect()` only — no old SIGNAL/SLOT macros
- Use `Q_PROPERTY` for all fields exposed to QML; always declare `NOTIFY` signal
- `Q_INVOKABLE` for methods callable from QML
- Pass `QObject*` parent to all QObject-derived constructors
- Use `Qt::UniqueConnection` when connecting in loops

## QML Integration
- Expose C++ objects to QML via `rootContext()->setContextProperty("name", object)`
- List models inherit `QAbstractListModel` and implement `rowCount`, `data`, `roleNames`
- Return `QVariantMap` / `QStringList` for simple data; use models for lists shown in ListView

## Error Handling
- File I/O returns `bool` success, emits `errorOccurred(QString message)` signal
- No silent failures — always emit signal or return false with a reason

## Example: Q_PROPERTY pattern
```cpp
// In header:
Q_PROPERTY(QString deviceModel READ deviceModel WRITE setDeviceModel NOTIFY deviceModelChanged)
QString m_deviceModel;

// In cpp:
QString deviceModel() const { return m_deviceModel; }
void setDeviceModel(const QString& v) {
    if (m_deviceModel == v) return;
    m_deviceModel = v;
    emit deviceModelChanged();
    setModified(true);
}
```
